<article>
    <h1>Peu&#xAD;geot 3008 cross&#xAD;over: A plucky pug</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200725/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-25"><time>2020-07-25</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Toh Yong Chuan&#xD;&#xA;to&#xAD;hyc@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>The Peu­geot 3008 cross­over is one of the most un­der­rated cars in Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>It was launched for sale here in 2017 with a flag­ship 1.6-litre tur­bocharged diesel en­gine.</p>
    <p>De­spite the diesel power plant, the cross­over im­presses with its re­fine­ment, ul­tra-mod­ern styling and chic cabin. It nearly clinched the Straits Times Car of the Year ti­tle in 2017, nar­rowly los­ing to the Lexus LC500.</p>
    <p>The diesel en­gine was dropped from the lo­cal line-up when the 3008 was facelifted last year, and re­placed with an­other equally im­pres­sive 1.6-litre petrol en­gine.</p>
    <p>The en­gine, how­ever, draws a $10,000 penalty un­der the Ve­hic­u­lar Emis­sions Scheme, which jacked up the sport util­ity ve­hi­cle’s (SUV) price. It cost more than $140,000 with COE when ST re­viewed it in May last year.</p>
    <p>This is where the new 1.2-litre power plant makes its mark.</p>
    <p>The smaller en­gine was in­tro­duced in the lo­cal line-up in March, be­fore the cir­cuit breaker. It does not at­tract any pol­lu­tion penalty and low­ers the price of the car ($108,888 with COE), mak­ing it more ac­ces­si­ble to buy­ers.</p>
    <p>A dip in per­for­mance is un­avoid­able as the en­gine is about 25 per cent smaller in ca­pac­ity.</p>
    <p>Horse­power (181hp versus 129hp) and torque (250Nm versus 230Nm) are also re­duced, trans­lat­ing i nto a l ower top speed of 197kmh from 222kmh and a slower cen­tury sprint of 10.9 sec­onds from 8.8 sec­onds.</p>
    <p>The smaller en­gine labours more to get the 1.3-tonne car go­ing from stand­still, but once on the move, I do not find the car un­der-pow­ered through­out a 107km test-drive.</p>
    <p>The eight-speed transmissi­on plays a big role in mak­ing the car drive­able.</p>
    <p>The am­ple num­ber of gears keeps the en­gine speed at an op­ti­mum 2,000rpm.</p>
    <p>Even at the cruis­ing speed of 90kmh to 100kmh on the ex­press­way, the tallest eighth gear does not kick in, un­less I use the pad­dle shifters to up­shift.</p>
    <p>The car av­er­ages about 6 litres/ 100km over the test-drive, which is close to the of­fi­cial fig­ure of 5.2 litres/100km. This is im­pres­sive, con­sid­er­ing that about a third of the dis­tance is not clocked on ex­press­ways.</p>
    <p>But whether it has a 1.2- or 1.6-litre en­gine, the 3008 cross­over will bowl drivers over with its up­mar­ket cock­pit and cabin.</p>
    <p>The gearshift lever is shaped like a joy­stick, the steer­ing wheel has a flat top and bot­tom, and a 12.3-inch vir­tual in­stru­ment dis­play can be per­son­alised so that driv­ing data and en­ter­tain­ment op­tions can be kept in the driver’s for­ward field of vi­sion.</p>
    <p>The Peu­geot 3008 was al­ready an at­trac­tive and well-equipped cross­over. Now, it has widened its ap­peal with a lower price tag.</p>

